n and clear aperture are editable assumptions.","assumptionNoCombiner":"No beam combiner loss is included."},"spotInfo":{"family":"Filters the source presets. Glass DC tubes are high-voltage glass lamps; RF sources are sealed metal or ceramic lasers with RF excitation.","sourcePreset":"Select a real source family/model. The app uses the published or representative beam diameter instead of asking you to guess it.","lampDetails":"Opens the selected lamp data stored in the app, including rated/peak watt, beam diameter, current limit when available, and source link.","measuredWatt":"Optional measured continuous output from your own lamp, preferably from a laser power meter. When filled, the percentage slider uses this value instead of the preset rated watt.","peakWatt":"Optional peak or maximum observed watt. It appears as a marker on the source graph and sets the top end of the watt curves when it is higher than the exact/rated watt.","ampValue":"Optional tube current from your ammeter in mA. If it is higher than the lamp's best current, beam stability is marked risky.","ampMeterType":"Analog meters are modeled with wider reading uncertainty than digital meters.","powerPercent":"The app converts this percentage to actual watt from the selected source rating or your measured exact watt. Example: 65% of a 100 W source is 65 W.","pulseHz":"Pulse or PWM frequency. It affects pulse energy and a small thermal-growth estimate. RF sources usually tolerate much higher frequency than glass tubes.","lensDiameter":"Physical lens diameter. The app assumes about 90% is clear aperture and warns if the incoming beam is too large.","focalLength":"Lens focal length. Shorter focal length gives a smaller spot and shorter depth of focus; longer focal length gives a larger spot and more working clearance.","lensShape":"Meniscus lenses usually reduce spherical aberration for CO2 focusing. Convex is modeled with a small quality penalty.","lensFinish":"PVD, CVD, and PRO represent coating/finish quality bands. They affect transmission, thermal growth, and the calculated finish factor.","cvdMaker":"If your CVD optic is II-VI/Coherent, the app applies a small transmission and thermal-quality improvement.","mirrorFinish":"Mirror coating/material controls per-mirror reflection and heat absorption at 10.6 um.","mirrorDiameter":"Mirror diameter is used as a clear aperture check. The app assumes about 85% usable clear aperture.","mirrorCount":"Number of mirrors between source and lens. Common gantry CO2 machines use three mirrors.","imperfectAlignment":"A small default penalty for real machines that are not perfectly centered through every optic.","alignmentLossPercent":"How much power to subtract for imperfect alignment through mirrors, nozzle, and lens. Typical real-world allowance is about 3-5% unless the machine was freshly aligned.","smokePresent":"Adds an atmosphere/smoke loss for poor extraction, dirty air path, or visible cutting smoke in the beam path.","extractorOn":"A working extractor helps because it removes smoke and plume from the beam path. In the model it reduces the smoke/plume loss, but it cannot recover mirror or lens losses.","extractorStrength":"Stronger extraction clears smoke faster. Weak extraction leaves more plume in the beam path; strong extraction reduces the modeled smoke loss.","mirrorTempC":"Optional mirror mount temperature after 60 minutes near 95% power. Hot mirror houses indicate absorption and contamination, so loss is increased.","useExpander":"A beam expander increases the beam diameter before the focus lens. It can reduce spot diameter, but can also exceed mirror or lens apertures.","expanderMultiplier":"Beam expander multiplication such as 2x, 3x, or 4x. The expanded beam is checked against mirror and lens clear apertures.","sourceBeam":"The nominal 1/e^2 beam diameter coming from the source or at the waist listed in the source spec.","selectedWatt":"Rated source watt multiplied by your power percentage.","spotDiameter":"